# Attention Is All You Need

**Authors:** Ashish Vaswani, Noam Shazeer, Niki Parmar, Jakob Uszkoreit, Llion Jones, Aidan N. Gomez, Łukasz Kaiser, Illia Polosukhin
**Published:** 2017 | **Venue:** NeurIPS 2017

## Overview

Introduces the [[Transformer Architecture]] — a sequence-to-sequence model relying solely on [[Self-Attention Mechanism|self-attention]] rather than recurrent or convolutional layers. Achieves 28.4 BLEU on WMT 2014 English-to-German translation, surpassing all prior models.

## Key Points

- **Multi-head attention** allows the model to attend to information from different representation subspaces simultaneously.
- **Positional encodings** (sinusoidal) substitute for recurrence to retain sequence order.
- **Encoder-decoder architecture**: 6 identical layers each; each layer has self-attention + feed-forward sub-layers.
- **Training speed**: substantially more parallelizable than RNNs — trains in 12 hours on 8 P100 GPUs for the base model.
- **Scaled dot-product attention**: `Attention(Q, K, V) = softmax(QK^T / √d_k) V`

## Entities Mentioned

- [[Google Brain]] — primary affiliation of the authors
- [[University of Toronto]] — Gomez affiliation
- [[Google Research]] — Uszkoreit affiliation

## Concepts Discussed

- [[Self-Attention Mechanism]] — the core mechanism introduced
- [[Transformer Architecture]] — the model architecture this paper defines
- [[Positional Encoding]] — technique to inject sequence position information
- [[Multi-Head Attention]] — the multi-subspace attention variant

## Notable Quotes

> "We propose a new simple network architecture, the Transformer, based solely on attention mechanisms, dispensing with recurrence and convolutions entirely."
