# Transformer Architecture

## Overview

A neural network architecture introduced in [[Attention Is All You Need]] (Vaswani et al., 2017). Replaces recurrence with [[Self-Attention Mechanism|self-attention]] to model relationships between all positions in a sequence simultaneously. The Transformer is the foundation of virtually every major large language model, including [[GPT]], [[BERT]], and [[T5]].

## Key Facts

| Property          | Value                                               |
| ----------------- | --------------------------------------------------- |
| Introduced        | 2017 (NeurIPS)                                      |
| Original use case | Neural machine translation                          |
| Core mechanism    | Multi-head self-attention + feed-forward layers     |
| Key advantage     | Full parallelism (no sequential dependency)         |
| Derived models    | BERT, GPT, T5, PaLM, LLaMA, Claude, and many more  |

## How It Works

The Transformer encodes input tokens via an **encoder stack** (for understanding) and generates output via a **decoder stack** (for generation). Each layer applies:

1. **[[Multi-Head Attention]]** — attend to all positions in parallel across multiple subspaces.
2. **Feed-forward network** — two linear transformations with a ReLU in between.
3. **Layer normalization + residual connections** — stabilize training.

[[Positional Encoding]] (sinusoidal or learned) is added to token embeddings to preserve sequence order.

## Related Entities

- [[OpenAI]] — developed GPT series based on Transformer decoder
- [[Google Brain]] — original authors' affiliation; developed T5 and PaLM
- [[Hugging Face]] — primary open-source hub for Transformer models

## Related Concepts

- [[Self-Attention Mechanism]] — the core computation inside each Transformer layer
- [[Positional Encoding]] — mechanism to inject sequence order
- [[Scaling Laws]] — empirical rules governing Transformer performance vs. compute

## Sources

- [[Attention Is All You Need]] — original paper defining this architecture
